It's no bathtub, but this hard bench won't let Mike Giberson fall asleep studying.

Getting a iumpstart to avoid
encl-of-the-semester cramming

Monica Mayk

For The Pitt News

Sitting in the bathtub is a great way to
relax. .

But it's also a great way to study.

Four or ﬁve years ago, Jeanne VV1atr, a
supplemental instruction specialist at Pitt's
Leaming Skills Center, told a student to read
his assignments in ﬂie bathtub when he had
trouble staying awake. That is, a bathtub
without hot water and bubblebath.

"It's comfortable enough for support but
not enough to drift off," said Wratr.

According to VV1atr, the tub's cold
porcelain and the bathroom's bright lighting
helped the student stay awake while reading,
and helped him get through the semester.

While students cram for ﬁnals, they

often realize that the entire process would be '

a lot easier if only they had stayed on top of
course work throughout the semester. But
while many students have jobs, participate
in campus activities and take courses that
require reading piles of material, few stu-
dents know how to keep from falling
behind. Sometimes, it just takes a little cre-
ativity. ‘

Wratr suggested students prioritize
using a large desk calendar and different-
colored ink Recording obligations like class
time, work hours and activities in black per-

manent marker will help students see where '

their leisure time lies. .2

_ "Everyone has the perception that they
have good time management," said Wiatr.
"When they see what they are actually doing
with their time, then they see where they
waste time."

After prioritizing and setting down
obligations in black, students can begin to
set aside effective study and relaxation time.
Vlfiatr stressed that students should plan
everything, even nap time, if they want to
prioritize and manage study time.

Barbara Stout, also a supplemental
instruction specialist for the Learning Skills
Center, said succeeding in a course often
depends on assessing what the professor
expects and deciding what work requires

long preparation time and what just needs

review. '

She suggests students divide course
work into four categories: "Things I don't
know and the professor wants me to loiow,"
"Things I know and the professor wants me
to know," "Things I don't know and I don't
need to know" and "'Ihings I know and don't
need to know." ‘ -

This method helps students concentrate
on the most important aspects of die course
while reading and studying.

Kevin Collins, a Placement Service
adviser at Pitt, stressed" that attending class
on a regular basis is the most important fac-
tor in keeping up with the material. Sharing
notes with friends just isn't enough.

"As you go to lecture, you're going to
develop not: just more knowledge of the
information, but more of an understanding
of the instructor's style, experience and val-
ues," he said. "All those will help you study
because you know what to focus on."

Collins encourages students to seek

help from professors, teaching assistants and '
the Leaming Skills Center early in the term

if they fall behind ,

V "You should never let things go and say
'It‘s too early‘ or ‘I feel stupid approaching
the inst1uctor,"' he said. "Don't let things go
until the end of the term"

For students looking to learn new ways
to study and manage time, the Learning
Skills Centerolfers free ﬁve-week study
skills workshops to help with textbook read-
ing, note taking, test taking, time manage-
ment and improving memory. The work-
shops are meant to teach students concrete
methods of studying and note taking that
will boost retention and understanding.

