DUBOULSBURG, Ca. — A scientist in California
stunned the world yesterday when he armounced his
successful cloning of lettuce leaves that taste like beef.

Ever since a researcher in Scotland successfully
cloned a sheep named “Dolly” last March, scientists
around the world have begun using the new technology

to alter animal, mineral and vegetable in the name of‘

progress.

“We began cloning guppies, but the $3 million cost
didn’t seem justiﬁed, considering we bought the origi-
nals for $.25 cents a dozen at the mall,” said California
researcher Norman Klaycher.

Numerous other cloning experiments failed for the
scientist. Thousands of cloned locusts, sea bass,
Flintstone vitamins and Tamagatchis now sit useless in
warehouse crates around Klaycher’s lab.

“If you’ve seen one, you’ve seen ‘em all,” the scien-
tist joked, nervously.

Success ﬁnally found Klaycher over an Eat’N Park
steak salad late one night. ' -

“I was sitting there, forking through my meal when
it hit me: What a waste! Why not use my cloning tech-
nology to combine the two?” '

The result —— beef-ﬂavored lettuce.

“Thanks to this alteration, their leaves should
excrete the protein bovine-4,” said Klaycher’s assistant,
Bea Kerr.

' “The next step will be taste—testing the lettuce heads.
If all goes as expected, they will be indistinguishable to
the human tongue from a New York Strip,” she added.
