Jay Yander
For The Pitt News

Even though it was on the road, the
Pitt men’s swimming and diving team
felt right at home in the West Virginia
University Pool on Saturday, as records
fell and expectations rose.

The men’s swim team handed West
Virginia and the University of Maryland-
Baltimore County 82 and 131 point loss-
es, respectively, at WVU on Saturday
afternoon. ’

Pitt’s 200-yard medley relay team of
Adam Kotkiewicz, Joe Stone, Jon
Haggerty and Jerry Koller broke the
WVU pool record with a time of 1:34.52.
A second relay team of Eric Stefanski,

Andy Cherep, Brian Elko _and Noah
Caplan also swam under the pool record
but ﬁnished second to their teammates.

“We’re very excited about the
record-setting weekend,” said Head
Coach Chuck Knoles. “Not just one relay
team, but two teams did it.”

The dual meet was a much-needed
competition as well as win for the
Panthers, since their last competitive
meet was back in November — almost
two months ago.

“I was very pleased with our ﬁrst win
of the season, being that it was our first
competition since November,” Knoles
said.

It was the first ever meeting between
Pitt and UMBC, but as the score reﬂects,

there were no surprises for the Panthers
— something Knoles was glad about.

“You always like to know something
about your opponent before you compete
against them,” Knoles said. “Nonnally,
we have an idea of who we’re about to
swim against.”

Sophomore Jerry Koller had a busy
yet successful meet by winning two indi-
vidual events — the 50-yard freestyle
and the 100-yard freestyle — and taking
part in the record-breaking 200-yard
medley relay victory.

Although injured with a bruised

hamstring, freshman Devin Meece

claimed a victory for ‘himself and for Pitt

with a first place ﬁnish in the 200-yard
breaststroke. “I like to see underclass-

men like Meece contribute to the team,”
Knoles said. “He’s even swimming with
a bad leg.”

The Pitt divers fared just as well with
victories by George “Andy” Anderson in
both the one- and three—meter spring-

board competitions.

“Andy really had a great day of div-
ing,” Knoles said. “That success should
continue for him.”

, The Panthers return to the water this
Saturday at 1 p.m. when they play host to

' Big East nemesis Villanova at Trees Pool.

Pitt will then travel to Boston to face
Harvard in a non-conference meet on
Saturday, Jan. 30. Pittsburgh Panthers
swimming and diving meets at Trees
Pool are free to students.

